Macedonians vote in referendum to change country's name
Macedonia's citizens voted on Sunday in a referendum to change the country's name to "Republic of North Macedonia." This move would resolve a decades-long dispute with Greece that blocked Macedonia's requests to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, claims that its northern neighbor’s name represents a claim to its territory and vetoed Macedonia’s accession to NATO and the EU.
Both governments drafted a deal in June that included a proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the majority Slavic population of Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov said that the referendum would not be voted on, and the boycott campaign raised doubts about whether participation would reach the minimum 50 percent needed to keep the referendum valid.
The question on the referendum ballot was: “Are you in favour of membership of the European Union and NATO through the recognition of the agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Greek Republic?”
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is the price worth admitting Macedonia, the country that emerged after the fall of Yugoslavia, to communities such as the EU and NATO.
“I came here today to vote for a future for the country, for young people in Macedonia to live freely under the auspices of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us,” said Olivera Georgievska, 79, from Skopje.
Although the vote is not legally binding, enough MPs have declared that they will respect the will of the voters and decide according to the result.
A change of name would require a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
The state election commission said that no irregularities had occurred during the referendum by 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters voted.
“I came to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, an elector in the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian MP Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their ballots in a Macedonian referendum on changing the name of the country, thanks to which it could join NATO and the European Union, in the Macedonian city of Strumica on September 30, 2018.
Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, stood in front of the parliament in Skopje and pulled the chairs in front of the tents built by opponents who wanted to boycott the referendum.
“We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to enter them with our heads up, not the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We may be a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they don’t want to accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia and become part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring needed investments to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20 percent.
"I am convinced that the vast majority will be in favour, because more than 80 percent of our citizens support the EU and NATO," Zaev said after casting his ballot.
He added that the resulting “yes” would be “a confirmation of our future.”
A poll published Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Political Survey said 30 to 43 percent of voters were going to the referendum — which is below the threshold of required participation.
Another survey, conducted by Macedonian TV station Telma, found that 57 percent of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent of those surveyed said they would vote yes.
For a referendum to be successful, participation must be 50 percent plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would be the first serious blow to the pro-Western government’s policy since it came to power in May last year.
