In all of Bolivia, cut off from the sea, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile in the bloody conflict of the 19th century is still alive – as is the desire to re-engulf the waters of the Pacific Ocean.
After five years of deliberations, Bolivia is awaiting the decision of the International Court of Justice on 1 October, which will be held on the first day of this year.
“Bolivia is on the rise, has a spirit of unity and balance and of course believes in a positive outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will be watching the decision of the international court on large screens across the country in the hope that the Hague tribunal will decide in favor of Bolivia that, after decades of interrupted negotiations, Chile will be obliged to negotiate the granting of sovereign access to the sea to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who will take part in next year’s controversial fight for re-election, also has something to say about Monday’s decision.
“Our return to the Pacific Ocean is within reach,” he said at the end of August.
However, some analysts are convinced that it is unlikely that the court will rule in favor of Bolivia – and if it did, not much would have changed.
The United Nations body based in the Netherlands has no power to allocate Chilean territory and said it would not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the international court’s ruling comes only six months after hearing the final arguments suggests that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And while there can be no doubt about the Bolivian arguments, it is possible that in recent years it has taken a step backwards.
"The issue of access to the sea has been taken over by the current Bolivian government," Zárate said.
Morales’ aggressive rhetoric undermined all of Chile’s remaining affiliation, she said.
Bolivia and Chile will one day continue negotiations, but after that it will be very difficult to maintain dialogue.
The two countries have not had an embassy since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltze, a representative of Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision would be unusually quick.
Monday will give Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of miscarriage and achieve mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also rejected the claim that Morales – still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – would use the maritime question as a political barrel.
