John Edward: Without language skills, a global citizen will not be able to
Scottish independent schools maintain excellent academic results and this trend continues in 2018 with another year of exceptional test results, further strengthening individual and collective achievements in sports, arts, music and other social activities.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools are trying to prepare students for further and higher education, a career according to their ideas and a place in the world as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement school curriculums tailored to its needs, we still perceive modern languages as a popular and sought-after subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “When you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
When you speak to him in his own language, you speak to his heart.”
It’s a strong reminder that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we can’t just rely on English.
From this year’s test results, we can see that languages are at the top of the table with the highest marks among independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved the highest grade A in Mandarin Chinese, 72 percent in German, 69 percent in French and 63 percent in Spanish.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as the basic skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now considered as subjects of choice in independent and other schools as equally important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics).
A 2014 UK Commission on Employment and Skills survey found that 17 percent of the reasons employers cited as problems with job vacancies were insufficient language skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more promising job opportunities are emerging that languages require, these skills become essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career a person chooses, if he or she is learning a second language, he or she will have a real advantage in the future with such a lifelong ability.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give a multilingual person an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent did not know how to speak any foreign language enough to be able to speak fluently, with French being the only language in which a large percentage of people (15 percent) got doubled.
Therefore, it is important for today’s children to invest in language learning.
Knowledge of several languages, especially the languages of developed economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will be different depending on what languages it teaches.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in terms of the future in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
No matter what your child is interested in, in independent schools, he will always be able to choose from a variety of languages and will be taught by experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
At present, it cannot be denied that, in the global business environment, languages remain essential to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should in fact be called “international communication abilities.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this opportunity, diversity and excellent quality to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it.
