North Korea will not unilaterally disarm "in any way" without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister said on Saturday that continuing sanctions had deepened mistrust of the United States and that the country would not unilaterally surrender its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual general assembly of the world institution that North Korea has taken “substantial countermeasures” over the past year, such as the halting of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of a nuclear test site, and a commitment not to expand nuclear weapons and technology.
"We do not see any corresponding response from the United States," he added.
"Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances it is impossible for us to be the first to unilaterally disarm," he said.
While Ri reiterated the well-known complaints of North Korea against Washington’s resistance to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual steps, his view was fundamental in that he did not immediately deny unilateral nuclear disarmament.
Ri referred to a joint position issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between the current U.S. president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump promised North Korea security.
North Korea tried to achieve a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States declared that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to release tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on nuclear disarmament first and increases the level of tension through sanctions to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner and even by opposing the “declaration of an end to the war,” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions will bring us to our knees is an illusion of people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that the ongoing sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim Jong Un and Trump, which the US president told the United Nations earlier this week.
However, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the other side of the nuclear disarmament issue was South Korea instead of the United States, the disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have been achieved."
Despite this, Rih’s tone differed dramatically from last year when he told the U.N. General Assembly that targeting U.S. territory with North Korean missiles is inevitable after “Mr. President Evil” Trump called Kim “a rocket launcher on a suicide mission.”
