Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
The goal of this year’s new course at Harvard University is to get all students more sleep in an effort to suppress the growing trend of studying all night long with the help of caffeine.
Scientists have found that students at a world-leading university are often helpless when it comes to the complete foundations of caring for their health.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Clinic, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
To establish the course, he was inspired by a lecture he gave on sleep deprivation and its impact on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about it now, in my final year?’
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the meaning of sleep, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, which was held this year for the first time, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and sports performance while improving overall health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health service, said the university decided to open the course when it found that students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the working week.
The hourly course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is a picture of the boarding room on the screen, where students can click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books, and learn about the effects of caffeine, light, and how lack of sleep affects sports performance and how important regularity is.
In the next part, participants will learn how long-term sleep deficits can increase the risk of heart attack, death, depression, and cancer.
A map of the university campus with interactive icons further encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know about it – just as everyone has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” added Professor Czeisler.
There is still a culture in which students are proud to be able to learn all night long, he says, adding that modern technology and growing pressure on students means sleep deprivation has become a growing problem.
Ensuring sufficient quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even against weight gain, because sleep deficits put the brain in a mode of starvation, so they are constantly feeling hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his seminars last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to try to implement the course at the university level.
He hopes that in the next step, it will be possible to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before embarking on a challenging study.
Prof. Czeisler advises students to set their alarm clock both at bedtime and at waking time, and to be aware of the damaging effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disturb them by disturbing them.
