Syria is “ready” for the return of refugees, says Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild a country devastated by more than seven years of war.
Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said in an interview with the United Nations General Assembly that conditions in the country are improving.
“Today, the situation here is more stable and safer because of progress in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rebuild areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normal conditions.
Now there are all the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country, which they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would welcome aid to rebuild the devastated country.
However, he stressed that he does not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that sponsored the uprising.
