Current status of red sludge: Concentrations drop in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasote
The latest report by the Florida Commission for the Protection of Fish and Wildlife shows a general drop in red sludge concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Florida Commission, in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier areas, uneven conditions have been reported in relation to the coating, indicating decreasing concentrations.
Red mud spans approximately 130 miles of coastline from the northern Pinellas to the southern districts of Lee.
Spots can be found about 10 miles from the coast in the Hillsborough area, but on a smaller number of places compared to last week.
Red mud was also observed in the Pasco area.
Average coastal or off-shore concentrations in the Pinellas area have been reported last week, low to high seas concentrations in the Hillsborough area, high seas concentrations in the Manatee area, high coastal or off-shore concentrations in the Sarasota area, average coastal or off-shore concentrations in the Le Colliere area, and high concentrations in the Charlotte area.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Respiratory tract irritation has not been reported in northwest Florida for the past week.
